Neoantigen Prediction 4

Using ESTIMATE to Calculate Immune Score

ESTIMATE (Estimation of STromal and Immune cells in MAlignant Tumor tissues using Expression data) is an R-based tool for calculating immune score. So, whats immune score in the first place? According to this article by Jrme Galon, et al., called The immune score as a new possible approach for the classification of cancer, the authors suggest a new way of classifying cancer based on a thing named immune score. Usually, the outcome prediction in cancer is done by examining and evaluating tissue samples obtained during surgical removal of the primary tuomr focusing on their histopathological characteristics. Tumor staging (AJCC/UICC-TNM classification, Wikipedia article: TNM staging system) classification was developed and maintained by the Union for International Cancer Control (UICC) and also is used by the American Joing Committee on Cancer (AJCC) and International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics (FIGO). This system is a global standard for classifying the extent of spread of cancer by stage through the anatomical extent of tumor cancers. It has gained wide international acceptance for many solid tumor cancers, but unfortunately not applicable to leukaemia and tumors in the CNS (central nervous system). TNM system goes like this: data on tumor burden (T), presence of cancer cells in draining and regional lymph nodes (N), and evidence for metastases (M). The thing about the histopathological analysis of tumor tissue reveals that tumors are often infiltrated by a variable degree of inflammatory and lymphocytic cells. Closer look reveals that these immune cells are not distributed randomly, but seem to be organized in more or less dense infiltrates in the center of the tumoral zone (CT), at the invasive margin (IM) of tumoral nests and in lymphoid islets adjacent to the tumor. Broad signatures of inflammation can tell us a lot about the biology of tumor. This signature includes evidence for innate immune activation, chemokines for T cell recruitment, immune effector molecules, and expression of immune regulatory factors. Global analysis of the tumor microenvironment showed that the immune contexture, i.e.the nature, functional orientation, density, and location of adaptive immune cells within distinct tumor regions influence the risk of relapse. Immune classification of tumors was proposed based on a simple score, quantifying the density and location of immune-cells within the tumor. This immune-classification has a prognostic value that may be superior to AJCC/UICC TNM-classification. Immune score basically tells us the quantitative representation of inflmmation for evaluation.

ESTIMATE provides researchers with scores for 1) tumor purity, 2) the level of stromal cells1 present, and the 3) infiltration level of immune cells in tumor tissues based on expression data.

In summary, ESTIMATE algorithm predicts and generates three following scores based on single sample Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (single-sample GSEA):

  1. stromal score (that captures the presence of stroma in tumor tissue),
  2. immune score (that represents the infiltration of immune cells in tumor tissue), and
  3. estimate score (that infers tumor purity).

The algorithm presumes the data is obtained from Affymetrix, but also can be used for properly normalized RNA-seq data. Heres a good read on this issue on biostars: https://www.biostars.org/p/279853/.

Heads up, the following procedure is from ESTIMATE vignette documentation in rforge.

Install ESTIMATE

Load libraries for practice

library(estimate) # ESTIMATE library for calculation
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

Youll notice package called gridExtra. ggplot2 uses grid package to generate graphics. gridExtra package provides a few additional functions that come in handy. For example, you can place multiple graphs in the virtual page.

Lets open GeneExpression.txt. This data is obtained from 10 ovaraian cancer samples using Affymetrix U133Plus2.0 platform. (Note that the data is also already pre-included in the package that you can load it over a system.file command, OvarianCancerExpr <- system.file("extdata", "sample_input.txt", package="estimate").)

You can see in the picture that gene expression values are sorted by samples (s516, s518, ).

Now, use filterCommonGenes function on gene expression data to filter for only the common genes. The row name in an input data must be gene symbols or Entrez gene IDs.

filterCommonGenes(input.f="GeneExpression.txt", output.f="OV_10412genes.gct", id="GeneSymbol")
## [1] "Merged dataset includes 10412 genes (0 mismatched)."
# filter for common genes.

Now that weve got our common genes sorted, we calculate stromal and immune scores that represent the presence of stromal and immune cells in tumor tissu, respectively. The function estimateScore measures raw ESTIMATE scores that are positively correlated with DNA copy number based tumor purity.

estimateScore("OV_10412genes.gct", "OV_estimate_score.gct", platform="affymetrix") #Score calculation
## [1] "1 gene set: StromalSignature  overlap= 141"
## [1] "2 gene set: ImmuneSignature  overlap= 141"

Once we ccalculate tumor purity, we can view the association between raw ESTIMATE score and tumor purity.

plotPurity(scores="OV_estimate_score.gct", samples="s516", platform="affymetrix") #Tumor Purity Plot drawing.
## Warning in dir.create(output.dir): 'estimated_purity_plots'  
## Plotting tumor purity based on ESTIMATE score

The purity plot is stored in estimated_purity_plots sub-directory.

You can see this if you look into the function plotPurity:

plotPurity <- function(scores,
                       samples="all_samples",
                       platform=c("affymetrix", "agilent", "illumina"),
                       output.dir="estimated_purity_plots") { ...
     ...}                  
...
## Create output directory
dir.create(output.dir)

Running time

Finally, heres a little tip on how to show the running time of the whole program by using proc.time().

ptm <- proc.time()
estimateScore("OV_10412genes.gct", "OV_estimate_score.gct", platform="affymetrix")
## [1] "1 gene set: StromalSignature  overlap= 141"
## [1] "2 gene set: ImmuneSignature  overlap= 141"
proc.time()-ptm
##    user  system elapsed 
##    0.22    0.00    0.21

Visualization of ESTIMATE score results

Earlier practice was about calculating scores for each sample, using samples expression data. Assume that we have calculated all TCGA samples (total 8,829 of them) scores (stromal score, immune [infiltration] score, ESTIMATE [tumor purity] score) scores with their gene expression data. The file TCGA_ESTIMATE_CLINICAL.txt contains this information.

TCGA_ESTIMATE_CLINICAL.txt file looks like below.

Now execute below codes for visualization. Load input file and see how the scores are distributed throughout three cancer types.

TCGAEstimate <- read.table("TCGA_ESTIMATE_CLINICAL.txt", header=T, '\t', row.names=1)
#input file loaded (8829 people)

Scores by Cancer Type

Stromal score by cancer type

# Boxplot visualization of scores by cancer type
stromal_cancer <- ggplot(TCGAEstimate, aes(x=Cancer_type, y=Stromal_score, fill=Cancer_type)) + geom_boxplot()

stromal_cancer

Immune score by cancer type

immune_cancer <- ggplot(TCGAEstimate, aes(x=Cancer_type, y=Immune_score, fill=Cancer_type)) + geom_boxplot()

immune_cancer

ESTIMATE score by cancer type

estimate_cancer <- ggplot(TCGAEstimate, aes(x=Cancer_type, y=ESTIMATE_score, fill=Cancer_type)) + geom_boxplot()

estimate_cancer

Now Check if scores differ by gender (sex).

Scores by Gender

Test if each scores have significant difference via t-test.

t.test(Stromal_score ~ Gender, data= TCGAEstimate) # analyze by Gender

Scores by age

Since age is a continuous variable, we need to take a different approach by taking the median, and comparing if there is a significant difference between group of people with younger age than median and group of people with older age than median value.

median_age <- median(as.numeric(TCGAEstimate$Age))
age_cat <- rep("low", dim(TCGAEstimate)[1]) # rep returns a vector with repeated values
# set all values to "low"
age_cat[which(as.numeric(TCGAEstimate$Age) > median_age)] <- "high"
# set all values that have higher age than the median age to "high"

# Add new column with age designation to TCGAEstimate data frame.
TCGAEstimate$age_cat <- age_cat

On a side note, rep, seq, and cbind are powerful basic functions in R, with applications in a wide variety of tasks. rep repeats characters and seq creates a sequence of characters. rep takes in two parameters, the value to be repeated and the number of times to repeat that value.

T-test if there are significant differences in each score.

t.test(Stromal_score ~ age_cat, data=TCGAEstimate)

## mean in group high  mean in group low
